name: NIH
tweet: (5/5): US is recommitted to working with partners to combat #AMR using a #OneHealth approach. A 5 year action plan will guide efforts through 2025. Together, we can be better stewards for global #PublicHealth & antimicrobials to protect future generations.  https://t.co/SjvBAiKBqZ

name: NIH
tweet: (4/5): The #COVID19 pandemic has shown that surveillance, early detection, containment, & having effective and accessible drugs when needed are key to stopping the spread of infections and disease. These lessons can be applied to #AMR strategies.

name: NIH
tweet: (3/5): Successful containment strategies have been developed, but the global community must scale up strategies to prevent infections and save lives. Together, more action is needed across settings, industries, and countries to fully protect people from #AMR threats.

name: NIH
tweet: (2/5): How do antimicrobials become resistant? With increased spread/use comes increased opps for mutations that help germs survive. While development of new drugs is important to treat #AMR threats, understanding resistant germs can help us slow spread & save lives more quickly.

name: NIH
tweet: (1/5): The development of antimicrobials is a marvel of modern medicine; however, progress is threatened by the escalation of antimicrobial resistance. More than 2.8 mil #AMR infections occur in the US each year & more than 35,000 people die as a result.  https://t.co/qv2SlrYz6x

name: NIH
tweet: .@NIHDirector on the Hill: I‚Äôm excited that we can respond to this crisis in record time & hopeful when I think of all the lives that have been saved from other diseases through vaccinations. We can save millions more by developing a safe, effective vaccine for #COVID19. #NIH

name: NIH
tweet: .@NIHDirector on the Hill: We‚Äôve also eliminated downtime by moving into new phases of vaccine research before previous phase is finished. However: the rigor of the scientific evaluation of safety and efficacy will NOT be compromised. #NIH

name: NIH
tweet: .@NIHDirector on the Hill: Safety is foremost in all our minds. We are moving quickly, but we can address traditional vaccine development delays w/o compromising safety. For example, carrying out previously sequential steps in parallel. #NIH

name: NIH
tweet: .@NIHDirector on the Hill: 3rd approach uses tech developed at #NIH: a snippet of messenger RNA (mRNA) from SARS-CoV-2 genome is injected, spurring human cells to make that protein and encourage production of antibodies.  https://t.co/be28hC3NJI

name: NIH
tweet: .@NIHDirector on the Hill: 2nd approach uses a harmless viral vector (adenovirus) to deliver a gene for the spike protein, which triggers immune response when adenovirus enters cells. #NIH  https://t.co/BUsyIAu8lu

name: NIH
tweet: .@NIHDirector on the Hill: The 1st approach is the traditional recombinant protein technology which uses injection of purified spike protein. #NIH  https://t.co/BvfgkDLmdb

name: NIH
tweet: .@NIHDirector on the Hill: The 6 vaccines use 3 diff. scientific approaches; diversity is best insurance against adverse issues. All aim to trigger immune response against coronavirus spike protein. #COVID19 survivors make antibodies to this spike&we need vaccine to do same #NIH  https://t.co/GxFnRr2hCB

name: NIH
tweet: .@NIHDirector on the Hill: Phase III participants will be closely followed over several weeks. A successful vaccine candidate should have many fewer cases of #COVID19 in ppl who received it vs those who received placebo. Participants are followed for 2 yrs to assess safety #NIH

name: NIH
tweet: .@NIHDirector on the Hill: 6 vaccine candidates for #COVID19 are ready for large scale trials after rigorous animal testing and Phase I testing in humans. 3 of 6 are already in Phase III testing: the goal is to inject 30k volunteers, half with vaccine and half with placebo. #NIH

name: NIH
tweet: .@NIHDirector on the Hill: Your immune system is like a factory that designs an antibody for every specific threat&keeps the blueprint. name: NIH
tweet: .@NIHDirector on the Hill: We are making significant strides at unprecedented speed in developing diagnostics, therapeutics & vaccines for #COVID19. Yet far more work is needed to end this global health crisis. With your support, #NIH is on the case!

name: NIH
tweet: .@NIHDirector on the Hill: A Phase 2 #clinicaltrial of this #COVID19 vaccine candidate began on May 29th. This month, #NIH plans to launch a Phase 3 clinical trial that will seek to enroll 30,000 volunteers, with results expected in a few months.

name: NIH
tweet: .@NIHDirector on the Hill: Furthest along in US testing is experimental vaccine from #NIH‚Äôs Vaccine Research Center, in partnership w/@Moderna_tx. It uses non-infectious snippet of mRNA to spur the body to make viral spike proteins, encouraging production of protective antibodies  https://t.co/mJ0d2bbme5

name: NIH
tweet: .@NIHDirector on the Hill: Still, the ultimate tool we need to end the #COVID19 pandemic is a vaccine. Operation Warp Speed & #ACTIV are working together intensively on vaccine development. A scientific review of more than 50 vaccine candidates has already been conducted. #NIH

name: NIH
tweet: .@NIHDirector on the Hill: Supported by Operation Warp Speed, we expect four treatment trials to get underway in the next six weeks‚Äîand we‚Äôre quite excited about their potential for success. #NIH

name: NIH
tweet: .@NIHDirector on the Hill: In 2 months, #ACTIV developed 5 master protocols to accelerate research trials & hasten @US_FDA review. These will rigorously test a series of antivirals, anticoagulants, immunomodulators & monoclonal antibody Txs in inpatient & outpatient settings #NIH

name: NIH
tweet: .@NIHDirector on the Hill: But it‚Äôs not enough to diagnose this disease. We must treat it, and, as soon as possible, prevent it. To that end, #NIH has launched the Accelerating COVID-19 Therapeutic Interventions and Vaccines, or #ACTIV, Initiative:  https://t.co/BTmUNX6pyG  https://t.co/RZJZSorqWE

name: NIH
tweet: .@NIHDirector on the Hill: By fall, we expect that the winning technology‚Äîor technologies‚Äîwill make it possible to deploy several million tests each week. (More on #RADx here:  https://t.co/3lwjPFaAI3) #NIH

name: NIH
tweet: .@NIHDirector on the Hill: #RADx aims to speed dev of testing technologies & fast-tracking most promising through a 3-phase innovation funnel. In ~2mo, #NIH received 2.4K+ expressions of interest, 560+ completed app. 23 are already undergoing intense validation in Phase 1.  https://t.co/SYrmNxMtBz

name: NIH
tweet: .@NIHDirector on the Hill: Scaling to rapid, routine point-of-care testing would be a major advantage but requires new tech. name: NIH
tweet: .@NIHDirector on the Hill: Testing in the US has also come a long way: 30M+ tests for presence of the #COVID19 have been administered in the last few months, more than in any other nation. Yet these tests are not entirely satisfactory for the needs at hand. #NIH

name: NIH
tweet: .@NIHDirector on the Hill: Based on hard work, we now have better means of treating #COVID19 than just a few months ago. Remdesivir and dexamethasone have proven beneficial in rigorous trials and are now standard of care for hospitalized patients. #NIH

name: NIH

name: NIH
tweet: .@NIHDirector on the Hill: None of this would be possible without your support. Because of you, we at #NIH are working hard to turn dreams of healing and health into reality for all.

name: NIH
tweet: .@NIHDirector on the Hill: These are dramatic times for #NIH research. Today, I focused on gene-based therapies. Many other remarkable advances are on the horizon, like vaccines for #coronavirus, addressing the opioid crisis, & immunotherapy for more types of cancer.

name: NIH
tweet: .@NIHDirector on the Hill: To that end, @POTUS FY20 Budget includes $30M initiative for #NIH-led consortium to shepherd dev of gene therapy targets for #rarediseases, from concept to clinic ‚Äì customizing processes for gene delivery, manufacture, regulatory review & testing.

name: NIH
tweet: .@NIHDirector on the Hill: We can rely on the private sector to support trials for more common diseases.  But for ultra-rare diseases, NIH must do more to de-risk projects, so we can interest potential partners from the private sector. #NIH

name: NIH
tweet: .@NIHDirector on the Hill: Five years ago, I‚Äôd never have predicted this explosion of opportunities in gene therapy. But actualizing this potential poses real challenges. It can take two years to produce the materials needed for clinical trials of gene-based therapies. #NIH

name: NIH
tweet: .@NIHDirector on the Hill: Latest development in gene-based treatments, the CRISPR, promises to boost that number. #CRISPR provides a precise ‚Äúfind & replace‚Äù function for DNA, allowing cells to be reprogrammed to correct disease-causing misspellings  https://t.co/o75AWUp4zl #NIH

name: NIH
tweet: .@NIHDirector on the Hill: But we need more breakthroughs.  There are about 6,500 diseases for which we know the molecular basis.  The pace of discovery has increased rapidly.  Yet we still have effective therapies for only ~500 of these conditions.  #NIH
